</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="915C1619FFD3B45B38D8F8CFA97DFDBF" blockId="13.[151,1437,222,571]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">
<subSubSection id="D9F94592FFD3B45B38D8F8CFA979FDBF" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" type="discussion">
<bibRefCitation id="F5726BE8FFD3B45B38D8F8CFA943FF73" author="Roux, J." box="[151,296,223,247]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" pagination="439 - 472" refId="ref10707" refString="Roux, J. (1928) Reptiles et Amphibiens de l'Indemeridionale. Revue suisse de zoologie, 35, 439 - 472. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 117624" type="journal article" year="1928">Roux (1928)</bibRefCitation>
described this subspecies which was relegated to the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="56E36D9AFFD3B45B3C0FF8CEAD43FF72" baseAuthorityName="Beddome" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[1088,1320,222,246]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Salea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anamallayana">
<emphasis id="A397CA0BFFD3B45B3C0FF8CEAD43FF72" box="[1088,1320,222,246]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">Salea anamallayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="F5726BE8FFD3B45B3D16F8CEA88EFE9F" author="Smith, M. A." pageId="13" pageNumber="576" refId="ref10790" refString="Smith, M. A. (1935) The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Fol. II. Sauria. T aylor and Francis, London, xiii + 440 pp., 2 folding maps, 1 pl." type="book" year="1935">Smith (1935)</bibRefCitation>
. It is, however, evident from Smith’s own writing that he made that decision after reading Roux’s description without actually examining the 
<typeStatus id="4E58A8BBFFD3B45B3AC4F937AAD4FEBB" box="[651,703,295,319]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">type</typeStatus>
. The 
<typeStatus id="4E58A8BBFFD3B45B3B4EF937AB5AFEBB" box="[769,817,295,319]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">type</typeStatus>
(NMB 9687), which is a female, has three triangular markings on the back instead of chevrons and a few smooth scales on flank (
<bibRefCitation id="F5726BE8FFD3B45B3BB4F95BAC11FEE7" author="Roux, J." box="[1019,1146,331,355]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" pagination="439 - 472" refId="ref10707" refString="Roux, J. (1928) Reptiles et Amphibiens de l'Indemeridionale. Revue suisse de zoologie, 35, 439 - 472. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 117624" type="journal article" year="1928">Roux 1928</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation id="09D80A9CFFD3B45B3CDEF95AAC9FFEE7" box="[1169,1268,330,355]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[170,1410,1221,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[170,1410,1221,1909]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Holotype of Salea anamallayana triangularis (Photo courtesy: Eduard Stöckli)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601496/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">Figure 8</figureCitation>
). The sporadic presence of smooth scales on flank is a common character seen in 
<taxonomicName id="56E36D9AFFD3B45B3BC2F97FAC20FE02" baseAuthorityName="Beddome" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[909,1099,366,390]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Salea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anamallayana">
<emphasis id="A397CA0BFFD3B45B3BC2F97FAC20FE02" box="[909,1099,366,390]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">S. anamallayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the colour pattern of this species is so variable that emphasis on this feature cannot be seriously considered. We could not detect any qualitative character from the photographs which would help us to distinguish this specimen from 
<taxonomicName id="56E36D9AFFD3B45B3DC8F9A7A95CFE77" baseAuthorityName="Beddome" baseAuthorityYear="1878" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Salea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anamallayana">
<emphasis id="A397CA0BFFD3B45B3DC8F9A7A95CFE77" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">S. anamallayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, the 
<typeStatus id="4E58A8BBFFD3B45B39B2F9CBAA46FE77" box="[509,557,475,499]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">type</typeStatus>
locality Marianshola in the Palni hills falls within the usual range of 
<taxonomicName id="56E36D9AFFD3B45B3DC8F9CBA95CFD92" baseAuthorityName="Beddome" baseAuthorityYear="1878" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Salea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anamallayana">
<emphasis id="A397CA0BFFD3B45B3DC8F9CBA95CFD92" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">S. anamallayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Hence, we can conclude that there is little justification in regarding NMB 9687 as a separate subspecies
</subSubSection>
.
</paragraph>
